# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: structure-based-drug-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] In contrast, substances that bind directly to an enzyme's active site or the binding site of the endogenous ligand of a receptor are called **orthosteric** regulators or modulators.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The site to which the effector binds is termed the *allosteric site* or *regulatory site*.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric sites allow effectors to bind to the protein, often resulting in a conformational change and/or a change in protein dynamics.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Effectors that enhance the protein's activity are referred to as *allosteric activators*, whereas those that decrease the protein's activity are called *allosteric inhibitors*.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric regulations are a natural example of control loops, such as feedback from downstream products or feedforward from upstream substrates.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Long-range allostery is especially important in cell signaling.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric regulation is also particularly important in the cell's ability to adjust enzyme activity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The term *allostery* comes from the Ancient Greek *allos* (ἄλλος), "other", and *stereos* (στερεός), "solid (object)".
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] This is in reference to the fact that the regulatory site of an allosteric protein is physically distinct from its active site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allostery contrasts with substrate presentation which requires no conformational change for an enzyme's activation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The term *orthostery* comes from the Ancient Greek orthós (ὀρθός) meaning "straight", "upright", "right" or "correct".
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Mechanism of Action: By occupying the active site, these inhibitors prevent the substrate from binding, thereby directly blocking the enzyme's catalytic activity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Competitive Inhibition: Most orthosteric inhibitors compete with the substrate for the active site, which means their effectiveness can be reduced if substrate concentration increases.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Mechanism of Action: Binding to the allosteric site induces a conformational change in the enzyme that can either reduce the affinity of the active site for the substrate or alter the enzyme's catalytic activity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] This indirect interference can inhibit the enzyme's function even if the substrate is present.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Non-Competitive Inhibition: Allosteric inhibitors often exhibit non-competitive inhibition, meaning their inhibitory effect is not dependent on the substrate concentration.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Many allosteric effects can be explained by the *concerted* MWC model put forth by Monod, Wyman, and Changeux, or by the sequential model (also known as the KNF model) described by Koshland, Nemethy, and Filmer.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Both postulate that protein subunits exist in one of two conformations, tensed (T) or relaxed (R), and that relaxed subunits bind substrate more readily than those in the tense state.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The two models differ most in their assumptions about subunit interaction and the preexistence of both states.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] For proteins in which subunits exist in more than two conformations, the allostery landscape model described by Cuendet, Weinstein, and LeVine, can be used.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric regulation may be facilitated by the evolution of large-scale, low-energy conformational changes, which enables long-range allosteric interaction between distant binding sites.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The concerted model of allostery, also referred to as the symmetry model or MWC model, postulates that enzyme subunits are connected in such a way that a conformational change in one subunit is necessarily conferred to all other subunits.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Thus, all subunits must exist in the same conformation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The model further holds that, in the absence of any ligand (substrate or otherwise), the equilibrium favors one of the conformational states, T or R.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The sequential model of allosteric regulation holds that subunits are not connected in such a way that a conformational change in one induces a similar change in the others.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Thus, all enzyme subunits do not necessitate the same conformation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Moreover, the sequential model dictates that molecules of a substrate bind via an induced fit protocol.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] While such an induced fit converts a subunit from the tensed state to relaxed state, it does not propagate the conformational change to adjacent subunits.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Instead, substrate-binding at one subunit only slightly alters the structure of other subunits so that their binding sites are more receptive to substrate.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The morpheein model of allosteric regulation is a dissociative concerted model.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] A morpheein is a homo-oligomeric structure that can exist as an ensemble of physiologically significant and functionally different alternate quaternary assemblies.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Transitions between alternate morpheein assemblies involve oligomer dissociation, conformational change in the dissociated state, and reassembly to a different oligomer.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The required oligomer disassembly step differentiates the morpheein model for allosteric regulation from the classic MWC and KNF models.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Porphobilinogen synthase (PBGS) is the prototype morpheein.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Ensemble models like the ensemble allosteric model and allosteric Ising model assume that each domain of the system can adopt two states similar to the MWC model.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The allostery landscape model introduced by Cuendet, Weinstein, and LeVine allows for the domains to have any number of states and the contribution of a specific molecular interaction to a given allosteric coupling can be estimated using a rigorous set of rules.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Molecular dynamics simulations can be used to estimate a system's statistical ensemble so that it can be analyzed with the allostery landscape model.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric modulation is used to alter the activity of molecules and enzymes in biochemistry and pharmacology.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] For comparison, a typical drug is made to bind to the active site of an enzyme which thus prohibits binding of a substrate to that enzyme causing a decrease in enzyme activity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric modulation occurs when an effector binds to an allosteric site (also known as a regulatory site) of an enzyme and alters the enzyme activity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric modulators are designed to fit the allosteric site to cause a conformational change of the enzyme, in particular a change in the shape of the active site, which then causes a change in its activity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] In contrast to typical drugs, modulators are not competitive inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] They can be positive (activating) causing an increase of the enzyme activity or negative (inhibiting) causing a decrease of the enzyme activity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The use of allosteric modulation allows the control of the effects of specific enzyme activities; as a result, allosteric modulators are very effective in pharmacology.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] In a biological system, allosteric modulation can be difficult to distinguish from modulation by substrate presentation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] An example of this model is seen with the enzyme pyruvate kinase of *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, a bacterium that is perfectly suited to adapt to living in the macrophages of humans.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The enzyme's sites serve as a communication between different substrates.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Sites like these also serve as a sensing mechanism for the enzyme's performance.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Positive allosteric modulation (also known as *allosteric activation*) occurs when the binding of one ligand enhances the affinity of other binding sites.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] An example is the binding of oxygen molecules to hemoglobin, where oxygen is both the physiological ligand and the modulator (or effector).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Here, the allosteric, or "other", site is the equivalent binding site of another protein subunit.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The binding of oxygen to one subunit induces a conformational change in that subunit that interacts with the remaining binding sites to enhance *their* oxygen affinity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] This type of allosteric modulation is also known as homotropic allostery or cooperativity as it describes the allosteric interaction between equivalent sites in an oligomeric protein.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Another example of allosteric activation is seen in cytosolic IMP-GMP specific 5'-nucleotidase II (cN-II), where the affinity for substrate GMP increases upon GTP binding at the dimer interface.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] As the two sites are not equivalent, this type of cooperativity is heterotropic.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Negative allosteric modulation (also known as *allosteric inhibition*) occurs when the binding of one ligand decreases the affinity for a ligand at other binding sites.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] For example, when 2,3-BPG binds to an allosteric site on hemoglobin, the affinity for oxygen of all subunits decreases.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Direct thrombin inhibitors provides an excellent example of negative allosteric modulation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric inhibitors of thrombin have been discovered that could potentially be used as anticoagulants.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Another example is strychnine, a convulsant poison, which acts as an allosteric inhibitor of the glycine receptor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Glycine is a major post-synaptic inhibitory neurotransmitter in mammalian spinal cord and brain stem.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Strychnine acts at a separate binding site on the glycine receptor in an allosteric manner; i.e., its binding lowers the affinity of the glycine receptor for glycine.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Thus, strychnine inhibits the action of an inhibitory transmitter, leading to convulsions.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Another instance in which negative allosteric modulation can be seen is between ATP and the enzyme phosphofructokinase within the negative feedback loop that regulates glycolysis.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Phosphofructokinase (generally referred to as PFK) is an enzyme that catalyses the third step of glycolysis: the phosphorylation of fructose-6-phosphate into fructose 1,6-bisphosphate.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] PFK can be allosterically inhibited by high levels of ATP within the cell.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] When ATP levels are high, ATP will bind to an allosteric site on phosphofructokinase, causing a change in the enzyme's three-dimensional shape.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] This change causes its affinity for substrate (fructose-6-phosphate and ATP) at the active site to decrease, and the enzyme is deemed inactive.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] This causes glycolysis to cease when ATP levels are high, thus conserving the body's glucose and maintaining balanced levels of cellular ATP.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] In this way, ATP serves as a negative allosteric modulator for PFK, despite the fact that it is also a substrate of the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] A homotropic allosteric modulator is a substrate for its target protein, as well as a regulatory molecule of the protein's activity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] It is typically an activator of the protein.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] For example, O2 and CO are homotropic allosteric modulators of hemoglobin.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Likewise, in IMP/GMP specific 5' nucleotidase, binding of one GMP molecule to a single subunit of the tetrameric enzyme leads to increased affinity for GMP by the subsequent subunits as revealed by sigmoidal substrate versus velocity plots.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] A heterotropic allosteric modulator is a regulatory molecule that is not the enzyme's substrate.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] It may be either an activator or an inhibitor of the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] For example, H+, CO2, and 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate are heterotropic allosteric modulators of hemoglobin.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Once again, in IMP/GMP specific 5' nucleotidase, binding of GTP molecule at the dimer interface in the tetrameric enzyme leads to increased affinity for substrate GMP at the active site indicating towards K-type heterotropic allosteric activation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] As has been amply highlighted above, some allosteric proteins can be regulated by both their substrates and other molecules.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Such proteins are capable of both homotropic and heterotropic interactions.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Some allosteric activators are referred to as "essential", or "obligate" activators, in the sense that in their absence, the activity of their target enzyme activity is very low or negligible, as is the case with N-acetylglutamate's activity on carbamoyl phosphate synthetase I, for example.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] A non-regulatory allosteric site is any non-regulatory component of an enzyme (or any protein), that is not itself an amino acid.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] For instance, many enzymes require sodium binding to ensure proper function.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] However, the sodium does not necessarily act as a regulatory subunit; the sodium is always present and there are no known biological processes to add/remove sodium to regulate enzyme activity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Non-regulatory allostery could comprise any other ions besides sodium (calcium, magnesium, zinc), as well as other chemicals and possibly vitamins.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric modulation of a receptor results from the binding of allosteric modulators at a different site (a "regulatory site") from that of the endogenous ligand (an "active site") and enhances or inhibits the effects of the endogenous ligand.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Under normal circumstances, it acts by causing a conformational change in a receptor molecule, which results in a change in the binding affinity of the ligand.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] In this way, an allosteric ligand modulates the receptor's activation by its primary orthosteric ligand, and can be thought to act like a dimmer switch in an electrical circuit, adjusting the intensity of the response.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] For example, the GABAA receptor has two active sites that the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) binds, but also has benzodiazepine and general anaesthetic agent regulatory binding sites.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] These regulatory sites can each produce positive allosteric modulation, potentiating the activity of GABA.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Diazepam is a positive allosteric modulator at the benzodiazepine regulatory site, and its antidote flumazenil is a receptor antagonist.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] More recent examples of drugs that allosterically modulate their targets include the calcium-mimicking cinacalcet and the HIV treatment maraviroc.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric proteins are involved in, and are central in many diseases, and allosteric sites may represent a novel drug target.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] There are a number of advantages in using allosteric modulators as preferred therapeutic agents over classic orthosteric ligands.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] For example, G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR) allosteric binding sites have not faced the same evolutionary pressure as **orthosteric sites** to accommodate an endogenous ligand, so are more diverse.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Therefore, greater GPCR selectivity may be obtained by targeting allosteric sites.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] This is particularly useful for GPCRs where selective orthosteric therapy has been difficult because of sequence conservation of the orthosteric site across receptor subtypes.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Also, these modulators have a decreased potential for toxic effects, since modulators with limited co-operativity will have a ceiling level to their effect, irrespective of the administered dose.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Another type of pharmacological selectivity that is unique to allosteric modulators is based on co-operativity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] An allosteric modulator may display neutral co-operativity with an orthosteric ligand at all subtypes of a given receptor except the subtype of interest, which is termed "absolute subtype selectivity".
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] If an allosteric modulator does not possess appreciable efficacy, it can provide another powerful therapeutic advantage over orthosteric ligands, namely the ability to selectively tune up or down tissue responses only when the endogenous agonist is present.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Oligomer-specific small molecule binding sites are drug targets for medically relevant morpheeins.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] There are many synthetic compounds containing several noncovalent binding sites, which exhibit conformational changes upon occupation of one site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Cooperativity between single binding contributions in such supramolecular systems is positive if occupation of one binding site enhances the affinity Δ*G* at a second site, and negative if the affinity isn't highered.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Most synthetic allosteric complexes rely on conformational reorganization upon the binding of one effector ligand which then leads to either enhanced or weakened association of second ligand at another binding site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Conformational coupling between several binding sites is in artificial systems usually much larger than in proteins with their usually larger flexibility.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The parameter which determines the efficiency (as measured by the ratio of equilibrium constants Krel = KA(E)/KA in presence and absence of an effector E ) is the conformational energy needed to adopt a closed or strained conformation for the binding of a ligand A.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] In many multivalent supramolecular systems direct interaction between bound ligands can occur, which can lead to large cooperativities.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Most common is such a direct interaction between ions in receptors for ion-pairs.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] This cooperativity is often also referred to as allostery, even though conformational changes here are not necessarily triggering binding events.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allostery is a direct and efficient means for regulation of biological macromolecule function, produced by the binding of a ligand at an allosteric site topographically distinct from the orthosteric site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Due to the often high receptor selectivity and lower target-based toxicity, allosteric regulation is also expected to play an increasing role in drug discovery and bioengineering.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The AlloSteric Database (ASD) provides a central resource for the display, search and analysis of the structure, function and related annotation for allosteric molecules.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Currently, ASD contains allosteric proteins from more than 100 species and modulators in three categories (activators, inhibitors, and regulators).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Each protein is annotated with detailed description of allostery, biological process and related diseases, and each modulator with binding affinity, physicochemical properties and therapeutic area.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Integrating the information of allosteric proteins in ASD should allow the prediction of allostery for unknown proteins, to be followed with experimental validation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] In addition, modulators curated in ASD can be used to investigate potential allosteric targets for a query compound, and can help chemists to implement structure modifications for novel allosteric drug design.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Not all protein residues play equally important roles in allosteric regulation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] The identification of residues that are essential to allostery (so-called "allosteric residues") has been the focus of many studies, especially within the last decade.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] In part, this growing interest is a result of their general importance in protein science, but also because allosteric residues may be exploited in biomedical contexts.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Pharmacologically important proteins with difficult-to-target sites may yield to approaches in which one alternatively targets easier-to-reach residues that are capable of allosterically regulating the primary site of interest.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] These residues can broadly be classified as surface- and interior-allosteric amino acids.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/allosteric-regulation] Allosteric sites at the surface generally play regulatory roles that are fundamentally distinct from those within the interior; surface residues may serve as receptors or effector sites in allosteric signal transmission, whereas those within the interior may act to transmit such signals.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] In biochemistry and pharmacology, a **ligand** is a substance that forms a complex with a biomolecule to serve a biological purpose.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] The etymology stems from Latin *ligare*, which means 'to bind'.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] In protein-ligand binding, the ligand is usually a molecule which produces a signal by binding to a site on a target protein.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] The binding typically results in a change of conformational isomerism (conformation) of the target protein.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] In DNA-ligand binding studies, the ligand can be a small molecule, ion, or protein which binds to the DNA double helix.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] The relationship between ligand and binding partner is a function of charge, hydrophobicity, and molecular structure.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Binding occurs by intermolecular forces, such as ionic bonds, hydrogen bonds and Van der Waals forces.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] The association or docking is actually reversible through dissociation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Measurably irreversible covalent bonding between a ligand and target molecule is atypical in biological systems.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] In contrast to the definition of ligand in metalorganic and inorganic chemistry, in biochemistry it is ambiguous whether the ligand generally binds at a metal site, as is the case in hemoglobin.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] In general, the interpretation of ligand is contextual with regard to what sort of binding has been observed.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Ligand binding to a receptor protein alters the conformation by affecting the three-dimensional shape orientation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] The conformation of a receptor protein composes the functional state.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Ligands include substrates, inhibitors, activators, signaling lipids, and neurotransmitters.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] The rate of binding is called affinity, and this measurement typifies a tendency or strength of the effect.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Binding affinity is actualized not only by host–guest interactions, but also by solvent effects that can play a dominant, steric role which drives non-covalent binding in solution.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] The solvent provides a chemical environment for the ligand and receptor to adapt, and thus accept or reject each other as partners.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Radioligands are radioisotope labeled compounds used in vivo as tracers in PET studies and for in vitro binding studies.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] The interaction of ligands with their binding sites can be characterized in terms of a binding affinity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] In general, high-affinity ligand binding results from greater attractive forces between the ligand and its receptor while low-affinity ligand binding involves less attractive force.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] In general, high-affinity binding results in a higher occupancy of the receptor by its ligand than is the case for low-affinity binding; the residence time (lifetime of the receptor-ligand complex) does not correlate.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] High-affinity binding of ligands to receptors is often physiologically important when some of the binding energy can be used to cause a conformational change in the receptor, resulting in altered behavior for example of an associated ion channel or enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] A ligand that can bind to and alter the function of the receptor that triggers a physiological response is called a receptor agonist.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Ligands that bind to a receptor but fail to activate the physiological response are receptor antagonists.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] High-affinity ligand binding implies that a relatively low concentration of a ligand is adequate to maximally occupy a ligand-binding site and trigger a physiological response.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Receptor affinity is measured by an inhibition constant or Ki value, the concentration required to occupy 50% of the receptor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Ligand affinities are most often measured indirectly as an IC50 value from a competition binding experiment where the concentration of a ligand required to displace 50% of a fixed concentration of reference ligand is determined.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] The Ki value can be estimated from IC50 through the Cheng Prusoff equation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Ligand affinities can also be measured directly as a dissociation constant (Kd) using methods such as fluorescence quenching, isothermal titration calorimetry or surface plasmon resonance.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Low-affinity binding (high Ki level) implies that a relatively high concentration of a ligand is required before the binding site is maximally occupied and the maximum physiological response to the ligand is achieved.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] In the example shown to the right, two different ligands bind to the same receptor binding site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Only one of the agonists shown can maximally stimulate the receptor and, thus, can be defined as a *full agonist*.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] An agonist that can only partially activate the physiological response is called a *partial agonist*.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] In this example, the concentration at which the full agonist (red curve) can half-maximally activate the receptor is about 5 × 10−9 Molar (nM = nanomolar).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Binding affinity is most commonly determined using a radiolabeled ligand, known as a tagged ligand.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] *Homologous competitive binding experiments* involve binding competition between a tagged ligand and an untagged ligand.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] MP-SPR also enables measurements in high saline dissociation buffers thanks to a unique optical setup.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Microscale thermophoresis (MST), an immobilization-free method was developed.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] This method allows the determination of the binding affinity without any limitation to the ligand's molecular weight.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] For the use of statistical mechanics in a quantitative study of the ligand-receptor binding affinity, see the comprehensive article on the configurational partition function.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Binding affinity data alone does not determine the overall potency of a drug or a naturally produced (biosynthesized) hormone.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Potency is a result of the complex interplay of both the binding affinity and the ligand efficacy.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Ligand efficacy refers to the ability of the ligand to produce a biological response upon binding to the target receptor and the quantitative magnitude of this response.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] This response may be as an agonist, antagonist, or inverse agonist, depending on the physiological response produced.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Selective ligands have a tendency to bind to very limited kinds of receptor, whereas non-selective ligands bind to several types of receptors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] This plays an important role in pharmacology, where drugs that are non-selective tend to have more adverse effects, because they bind to several other receptors in addition to the one generating the desired effect.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] PIP2) in complex with a hydrophobic protein (e.g. lipid-gated ion channels) determining the affinity is complicated by non-specific hydrophobic interactions.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Non-specific hydrophobic interactions can be overcome when the affinity of the ligand is high.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] For example, PIP2 binds with high affinity to PIP2 gated ion channels.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Bivalent ligands consist of two drug-like molecules (pharmacophores or ligands) connected by an inert linker.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] There are various kinds of bivalent ligands and are often classified based on what the pharmacophores target.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Homobivalent ligands target two of the same receptor types.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Heterobivalent ligands target two different receptor types.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Bitopic ligands target an orthosteric binding sites and allosteric binding sites on the same receptor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] In scientific research, bivalent ligands have been used to study receptor dimers and to investigate their properties.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] This class of ligands was pioneered by Philip S.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Portoghese and coworkers while studying the opioid receptor system.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Bivalent ligands were also reported early on by Micheal Conn and coworkers for the gonadotropin-releasing hormone receptor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Since these early reports, there have been many bivalent ligands reported for various G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR) systems including cannabinoid, serotonin, oxytocin, and melanocortin receptor systems, and for GPCR-LIC systems (D2 and nACh receptors).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Bivalent ligands usually tend to be larger than their monovalent counterparts, and therefore, not 'drug-like' as in Lipinski's rule of five.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Many believe this limits their applicability in clinical settings.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] In spite of these beliefs, there have been many ligands that have reported successful pre-clinical animal studies.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Given that some bivalent ligands can have many advantages compared to their monovalent counterparts (such as tissue selectivity, increased binding affinity, and increased potency or efficacy), bivalents may offer some clinical advantages as well.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Ligands of proteins can be characterized also by the number of protein chains they bind.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] "Monodesmic" ligands (μόνος: single, δεσμός: binding) are ligands that bind a single protein chain, while "polydesmic" ligands (πολοί: many) are frequent in protein complexes, and are ligands that bind more than one protein chain, typically in or near protein interfaces.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Recent research shows that the type of ligands and binding site structure has profound consequences for the evolution, function, allostery and folding of protein compexes.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] A privileged scaffold is a molecular framework or chemical moiety that is statistically recurrent among known drugs or among a specific array of biologically active compounds.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] These privileged elements can be used as a basis for designing new active biological compounds or compound libraries.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] The dramatically increased computing power of supercomputers and personal computers has made it possible to study protein–ligand interactions also by means of computational chemistry.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] For example, a worldwide grid of well over a million ordinary PCs was harnessed for cancer research in the project grid.org, which ended in April 2007.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/binding-affinity] Grid.org has been succeeded by similar projects such as World Community Grid, Human Proteome Folding Project, Compute Against Cancer and Folding@Home.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The phrase "drug design" is similar to ligand design (i.e., design of a molecule that will bind tightly to its target).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Although design techniques for prediction of binding affinity are reasonably successful, there are many other properties, such as bioavailability, metabolic half-life, and side effects, that first must be optimized before a ligand can become a safe and effective drug.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] These other characteristics are often difficult to predict with rational design techniques.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Furthermore, in vitro experiments complemented with computation methods are increasingly used in early drug discovery to select compounds with more favorable ADME (absorption, distribution, metabolism, and excretion) and toxicological profiles.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] A biomolecular target (most commonly a protein or a nucleic acid) is a key molecule involved in a particular metabolic or signaling pathway that is associated with a specific disease condition or pathology or to the infectivity or survival of a microbial pathogen.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Potential drug targets are not necessarily disease causing but must by definition be disease modifying.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] In some cases, small molecules will be designed to enhance or inhibit the target function in the specific disease modifying pathway.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Small molecules (for example receptor agonists, antagonists, inverse agonists, or modulators; enzyme activators or inhibitors; or ion channel openers or blockers) will be designed that are complementary to the binding site of target.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Small molecules (drugs) can be designed so as not to affect any other important "off-target" molecules (often referred to as antitargets) since drug interactions with off-target molecules may lead to undesirable side effects.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Due to similarities in binding sites, closely related targets identified through sequence homology have the highest chance of cross reactivity and hence highest side effect potential.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Most commonly, drugs are organic small molecules produced through chemical synthesis, but biopolymer-based drugs (also known as biopharmaceuticals) produced through biological processes are becoming increasingly more common.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] In addition, mRNA-based gene silencing technologies may have therapeutic applications.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] For example, nanomedicines based on mRNA can streamline and expedite the drug development process, enabling transient and localized expression of immunostimulatory molecules.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] In vitro transcribed (IVT) mRNA allows for delivery to various accessible cell types via the blood or alternative pathways.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The use of IVT mRNA serves to convey specific genetic information into a person's cells, with the primary objective of preventing or altering a particular disease.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Phenotypic drug discovery is a traditional drug discovery method, also known as forward pharmacology or classical pharmacology.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] It uses the process of phenotypic screening on collections of synthetic small molecules, natural products, or extracts within chemical libraries to pinpoint substances exhibiting beneficial therapeutic effects.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] This method is to first discover the in vivo or in vitro functional activity of drugs (such as extract drugs or natural products), and then perform target identification.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Phenotypic discovery uses a practical and target-independent approach to generate initial leads, aiming to discover pharmacologically active compounds and therapeutics that operate through novel drug mechanisms.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] This method allows the exploration of disease phenotypes to find potential treatments for conditions with unknown, complex, or multifactorial origins, where the understanding of molecular targets is insufficient for effective intervention.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Rational drug design (also called reverse pharmacology) begins with a hypothesis that modulation of a specific biological target may have therapeutic value.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] In order for a biomolecule to be selected as a drug target, two essential pieces of information are required.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The first is evidence that modulation of the target will be disease modifying.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] This knowledge may come from, for example, disease linkage studies that show an association between mutations in the biological target and certain disease states.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The second is that the target is capable of binding to a small molecule and that its activity can be modulated by the small molecule.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Once a suitable target has been identified, the target is normally cloned and produced and purified.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The purified protein is then used to establish a screening assay.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] In addition, the three-dimensional structure of the target may be determined.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The search for small molecules that bind to the target is begun by screening libraries of potential drug compounds.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] This may be done by using the screening assay (a "wet screen").
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] In addition, if the structure of the target is available, a virtual screen may be performed of candidate drugs.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Ideally, the candidate drug compounds should be "drug-like", that is they should possess properties that are predicted to lead to oral bioavailability, adequate chemical and metabolic stability, and minimal toxic effects.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Several methods are available to estimate druglikeness such as Lipinski's Rule of Five and a range of scoring methods such as lipophilic efficiency.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Several methods for predicting drug metabolism have also been proposed in the scientific literature.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Due to the large number of drug properties that must be simultaneously optimized during the design process, multi-objective optimization techniques are sometimes employed.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Finally because of the limitations in the current methods for prediction of activity, drug design is still very much reliant on serendipity and bounded rationality.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The most fundamental goal in drug design is to predict whether a given molecule will bind to a target and if so how strongly.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Molecular mechanics or molecular dynamics is most often used to estimate the strength of the intermolecular interaction between the small molecule and its biological target.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] These methods are also used to predict the conformation of the small molecule and to model conformational changes in the target that may occur when the small molecule binds to it.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Molecular mechanics methods may also be used to provide semi-quantitative prediction of the binding affinity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Also, knowledge-based scoring function may be used to provide binding affinity estimates.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] These methods use linear regression, machine learning, neural nets or other statistical techniques to derive predictive binding affinity equations by fitting experimental affinities to computationally derived interaction energies between the small molecule and the target.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Ideally, the computational method will be able to predict affinity before a compound is synthesized and hence in theory only one compound needs to be synthesized, saving enormous time and cost.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The reality is that present computational methods are imperfect and provide, at best, only qualitatively accurate estimates of affinity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] In practice, it requires several iterations of design, synthesis, and testing before an optimal drug is discovered.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Computational methods have accelerated discovery by reducing the number of iterations required and have often provided novel structures.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] In order to overcome the insufficient prediction of binding affinity calculated by recent scoring functions, the protein-ligand interaction and compound 3D structure information are used for analysis.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] There are two major types of drug design.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The first is referred to as ligand-based drug design and the second, structure-based drug design.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Ligand-based drug design (or *indirect drug design*) relies on knowledge of other molecules that bind to the biological target of interest.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] These other molecules may be used to derive a pharmacophore model that defines the minimum necessary structural characteristics a molecule must possess in order to bind to the target.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] A model of the biological target may be built based on the knowledge of what binds to it, and this model in turn may be used to design new molecular entities that interact with the target.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Alternatively, a quantitative structure-activity relationship (QSAR), in which a correlation between calculated properties of molecules and their experimentally determined biological activity, may be derived.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] These QSAR relationships in turn may be used to predict the activity of new analogs.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Structure-based drug design (or *direct drug design*) relies on knowledge of the three dimensional structure of the biological target obtained through methods such as x-ray crystallography or NMR spectroscopy.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] If an experimental structure of a target is not available, it may be possible to create a homology model of the target based on the experimental structure of a related protein.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Using the structure of the biological target, candidate drugs that are predicted to bind with high affinity and selectivity to the target may be designed using interactive graphics and the intuition of a medicinal chemist.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Alternatively, various automated computational procedures may be used to suggest new drug candidates.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Current methods for structure-based drug design can be divided roughly into three main categories.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The first method is identification of new ligands for a given receptor by searching large databases of 3D structures of small molecules to find those fitting the binding pocket of the receptor using fast approximate docking programs.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] This method is known as virtual screening.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] A second category is de novo design of new ligands.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] In this method, ligand molecules are built up within the constraints of the binding pocket by assembling small pieces in a stepwise manner.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] These pieces can be either individual atoms or molecular fragments.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The key advantage of such a method is that novel structures, not contained in any database, can be suggested.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] A third method is the optimization of known ligands by evaluating proposed analogs within the binding cavity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Binding site identification is the first step in structure based design.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] If the structure of the target or a sufficiently similar homolog is determined in the presence of a bound ligand, then the ligand should be observable in the structure in which case location of the binding site is trivial.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] However, there may be unoccupied allosteric binding sites that may be of interest.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Furthermore, it may be that only apoprotein (protein without ligand) structures are available and the reliable identification of unoccupied sites that have the potential to bind ligands with high affinity is non-trivial.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] In brief, binding site identification usually relies on identification of concave surfaces on the protein that can accommodate drug sized molecules that also possess appropriate "hot spots" (hydrophobic surfaces, hydrogen bonding sites, etc.) that drive ligand binding.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Structure-based drug design attempts to use the structure of proteins as a basis for designing new ligands by applying the principles of molecular recognition.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Selective high affinity binding to the target is generally desirable since it leads to more efficacious drugs with fewer side effects.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Thus, one of the most important principles for designing or obtaining potential new ligands is to predict the binding affinity of a certain ligand to its target (and known antitargets) and use the predicted affinity as a criterion for selection.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] One early general-purposed empirical scoring function to describe the binding energy of ligands to receptors was developed by Böhm.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The basic idea is that the overall binding free energy can be decomposed into independent components that are known to be important for the binding process.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Each component reflects a certain kind of free energy alteration during the binding process between a ligand and its target receptor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The Master Equation is the linear combination of these components.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] According to Gibbs free energy equation, the relation between dissociation equilibrium constant, Kd, and the components of free energy was built.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Various computational methods are used to estimate each of the components of the master equation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] For example, the change in polar surface area upon ligand binding can be used to estimate the desolvation energy.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The number of rotatable bonds frozen upon ligand binding is proportional to the motion term.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The configurational or strain energy can be estimated using molecular mechanics calculations.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Finally the interaction energy can be estimated using methods such as the change in non polar surface, statistically derived potentials of mean force, the number of hydrogen bonds formed, etc.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] In practice, the components of the master equation are fit to experimental data using multiple linear regression.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] This can be done with a diverse training set including many types of ligands and receptors to produce a less accurate but more general "global" model or a more restricted set of ligands and receptors to produce a more accurate but less general "local" model.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] A particular example of rational drug design involves the use of three-dimensional information about biomolecules obtained from such techniques as X-ray crystallography and NMR spectroscopy.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Computer-aided drug design in particular becomes much more tractable when there is a high-resolution structure of a target protein bound to a potent ligand.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] This approach to drug discovery is sometimes referred to as structure-based drug design.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] The first unequivocal example of the application of structure-based drug design leading to an approved drug is the carbonic anhydrase inhibitor dorzolamide, which was approved in 1995.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Another case study in rational drug design is imatinib, a tyrosine kinase inhibitor designed specifically for the *bcr-abl* fusion protein that is characteristic for Philadelphia chromosome-positive leukemias (chronic myelogenous leukemia and occasionally acute lymphocytic leukemia).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Imatinib is substantially different from previous drugs for cancer, as most agents of chemotherapy simply target rapidly dividing cells, not differentiating between cancer cells and other tissues.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Types of drug screening include phenotypic screening, high-throughput screening, and virtual screening.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Phenotypic screening is characterized by the process of screening drugs using cellular or animal disease models to identify compounds that alter the phenotype and produce beneficial disease-related effects.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Emerging technologies in high-throughput screening substantially enhance processing speed and decrease the required detection volume.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Virtual screening is completed by computer, enabling a large number of molecules can be screened with a short cycle and low cost.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] Virtual screening uses a range of computational methods that empower chemists to reduce extensive virtual libraries into more manageable sizes.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/drug-design] It has been argued that the highly rigid and focused nature of rational drug design suppresses serendipity in drug discovery.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] An **enzyme inhibitor** is a molecule that binds to an enzyme and blocks its activity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzymes are proteins that speed up chemical reactions necessary for life, in which substrate molecules are converted into products.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] An enzyme facilitates a specific chemical reaction by binding the substrate to its active site, a specialized area on the enzyme that accelerates the most difficult step of the reaction.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] An enzyme inhibitor stops ("inhibits") this process, either by binding to the enzyme's active site (thus preventing the substrate itself from binding) or by binding to another site on the enzyme such that the enzyme's catalysis of the reaction is blocked.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors may bind reversibly or irreversibly.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors form a chemical bond with the enzyme such that the enzyme is inhibited until the chemical bond is broken.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] By contrast, reversible inhibitors bind non-covalently and may spontaneously leave the enzyme, allowing the enzyme to resume its function.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibitors produce different types of inhibition depending on whether they bind to the enzyme, the enzyme-substrate complex, or both.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors play an important role in all cells, since they are generally specific to one enzyme each and serve to control that enzyme's activity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, enzymes in a metabolic pathway may be inhibited by molecules produced later in the pathway, thus curtailing the production of molecules that are no longer needed.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This type of negative feedback is an important way to maintain balance in a cell.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors also control essential enzymes such as proteases or nucleases that, if left unchecked, may damage a cell.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Many poisons produced by animals or plants are enzyme inhibitors that block the activity of crucial enzymes in prey or predators.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Many drug molecules are enzyme inhibitors that inhibit an aberrant human enzyme or an enzyme critical for the survival of a pathogen such as a virus, bacterium or parasite.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Examples include methotrexate (used in chemotherapy and in treating rheumatic arthritis) and the protease inhibitors used to treat HIV/AIDS.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Since anti-pathogen inhibitors generally target only one enzyme, such drugs are highly specific and generally produce few side effects in humans, provided that no analogous enzyme is found in humans.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] (This is often the case, since such pathogens and humans are genetically distant.) Medicinal enzyme inhibitors often have low dissociation constants, meaning that only a minute amount of the inhibitor is required to inhibit the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] A low concentration of the enzyme inhibitor reduces the risk for liver and kidney damage and other adverse drug reactions in humans.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence the discovery and refinement of enzyme inhibitors is an active area of research in biochemistry and pharmacology.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors are a chemically diverse set of substances that range in size from organic small molecules to macromolecular proteins.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Small molecule inhibitors include essential primary metabolites that inhibit upstream enzymes that produce those metabolites.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This provides a negative feedback loop that prevents over production of metabolites and thus maintains cellular homeostasis (steady internal conditions).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Small molecule enzyme inhibitors also include secondary metabolites, which are not essential to the organism that produces them, but provide the organism with an evolutionary advantage, in that they can be used to repel predators or competing organisms or immobilize prey.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In addition, many drugs are small molecule enzyme inhibitors that target either disease-modifying enzymes in the patient or enzymes in pathogens which are required for the growth and reproduction of the pathogen.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In addition to small molecules, some proteins act as enzyme inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The most prominent example are serpins (**ser**ine **p**rotease **in**hibitors) which are produced by animals to protect against inappropriate enzyme activation and by plants to prevent predation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Another class of inhibitor proteins is the ribonuclease inhibitors, which bind to ribonucleases in one of the tightest known protein–protein interactions.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] A special case of protein enzyme inhibitors are zymogens that contain an autoinhibitory N-terminal peptide that binds to the active site of enzyme that intramolecularly blocks its activity as a protective mechanism against uncontrolled catalysis.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The N‑terminal peptide is cleaved (split) from the zymogen enzyme precursor by another enzyme to release an active enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The binding site of inhibitors on enzymes is most commonly the same site that binds the substrate of the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] These active site inhibitors are known as orthosteric ("regular" orientation) inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The mechanism of orthosteric inhibition is simply to prevent substrate binding to the enzyme through direct competition which in turn prevents the enzyme from catalysing the conversion of substrates into products.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Alternatively, the inhibitor can bind to a site remote from the enzyme active site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] These are known as allosteric ("alternative" orientation) inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Kinetic mechanisms for reversible inhibition.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate (S) binding to enzyme (E) in blue, catalysis releasing product (P) in red, inhibitor (I) binding to enzyme in green.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Binding site in blue, substrate in black, inhibitor in green, and allosteric site in light green.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Competitive inhibitors usually bind to the active site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Non-competitive bind to a remote (allosteric) site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Uncompetitive inhibitors only bind once the substrate is bound, fully disrupting catalysis, and mixed inhibition is similar but with only partial disruption of catalysis.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibitors attach to enzymes with non-covalent interactions such as hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions and ionic bonds.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Multiple weak bonds between the inhibitor and the enzyme active site combine to produce strong and specific binding.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In contrast to irreversible inhibitors, reversible inhibitors generally do not undergo chemical reactions when bound to the enzyme and can be easily removed by dilution or dialysis.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] A special case is **covalent reversible inhibitors** that form a chemical bond with the enzyme, but the bond can be cleaved so the inhibition is fully reversible.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibitors are generally categorized into four types, as introduced by Cleland in 1963.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] They are classified according to the effect of the inhibitor on the *Vmax* (maximum reaction rate catalysed by the enzyme) and *Km* (the concentration of substrate resulting in half maximal enzyme activity) as the concentration of the enzyme's substrate is varied.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In competitive inhibition the substrate and inhibitor cannot bind to the enzyme at the same time.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This usually results from the inhibitor having an affinity for the active site of an enzyme where the substrate also binds; the substrate and inhibitor *compete* for access to the enzyme's active site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This type of inhibition can be overcome by sufficiently high concentrations of substrate (*Vmax* remains constant), i.e., by out-competing the inhibitor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] However, the apparent *Km* will increase as it takes a higher concentration of the substrate to reach the *Km* point, or half the *Vmax*.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Competitive inhibitors are often similar in structure to the real substrate (see for example the "methotrexate versus folate" figure in the "Drugs" section).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In uncompetitive inhibition the inhibitor binds only to the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In non-competitive inhibition the binding of the inhibitor to the enzyme reduces its activity but does not affect the binding of substrate.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This type of inhibitor binds with equal affinity to the free enzyme as to the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] It can be thought of as having the ability of competitive and uncompetitive inhibitors, but with no preference to either type.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] As a result, the extent of inhibition depends only on the concentration of the inhibitor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] *Vmax* will decrease due to the inability for the reaction to proceed as efficiently, but *Km* will remain the same as the actual binding of the substrate, by definition, will still function properly.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In mixed inhibition the inhibitor may bind to the enzyme whether or not the substrate has already bound.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence mixed inhibition is a combination of competitive and noncompetitive inhibition.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Furthermore, the affinity of the inhibitor for the free enzyme and the enzyme-substrate complex may differ.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] By increasing concentrations of substrate [S], this type of inhibition can be reduced (due to the competitive contribution), but not entirely overcome (due to the noncompetitive component).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Although it is possible for mixed-type inhibitors to bind in the active site, this type of inhibition generally results from an allosteric effect where the inhibitor binds to a different site on an enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibitor binding to this allosteric site changes the conformation (that is, the tertiary structure or three-dimensional shape) of the enzyme so that the affinity of the substrate for the active site is reduced.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] These four types of inhibition can also be distinguished by the effect of increasing the substrate concentration [S] on the degree of inhibition caused by a given amount of inhibitor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] For competitive inhibition the degree of inhibition is reduced by increasing [S], for noncompetitive inhibition the degree of inhibition is unchanged, and for uncompetitive (also called anticompetitive) inhibition the degree of inhibition increases with [S].
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible inhibition can be described quantitatively in terms of the inhibitor's binding to the enzyme and to the enzyme-substrate complex, and its effects on the kinetic constants of the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In the classic Michaelis-Menten scheme (shown in the "inhibition mechanism schematic" diagram), an enzyme (E) binds to its substrate (S) to form the enzyme–substrate complex ES.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Upon catalysis, this complex breaks down to release product P and free enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The inhibitor (I) can bind to either E or ES with the dissociation constants *K*i or *K*i', respectively.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] When an enzyme has multiple substrates, inhibitors can show different types of inhibition depending on which substrate is considered.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This results from the active site containing two different binding sites within the active site, one for each substrate.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, an inhibitor might compete with substrate A for the first binding site, but be a non-competitive inhibitor with respect to substrate B in the second binding site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Traditionally reversible enzyme inhibitors have been classified as competitive, uncompetitive, or non-competitive, according to their effects on *K*m and *V*max.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] These three types of inhibition result respectively from the inhibitor binding only to the enzyme E in the absence of substrate S, to the enzyme–substrate complex ES, or to both.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The division of these classes arises from a problem in their derivation and results in the need to use two different binding constants for one binding event.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] It is further assumed that binding of the inhibitor to the enzyme results in 100% inhibition and fails to consider the possibility of partial inhibition.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The common form of the inhibitory term also obscures the relationship between the inhibitor binding to the enzyme and its relationship to any other binding term be it the Michaelis–Menten equation or a dose response curve associated with ligand receptor binding.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This rearrangement demonstrates that similar to the Michaelis–Menten equation, the maximal rate of reaction depends on the proportion of the enzyme population interacting with its substrate.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] the effect of the inhibitor is a result of the percent of the enzyme population interacting with inhibitor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The only problem with this equation in its present form is that it assumes absolute inhibition of the enzyme with inhibitor binding, when in fact there can be a wide range of effects anywhere from 100% inhibition of substrate turn over to no inhibition.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] To account for this the equation can be easily modified to allow for different degrees of inhibition by including a delta *V*max term.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This term can then define the residual enzymatic activity present when the inhibitor is interacting with individual enzymes in the population.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] However the inclusion of this term has the added value of allowing for the possibility of activation if the secondary *V*max term turns out to be higher than the initial term.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] To account for the possibly of activation as well the notation can then be rewritten replacing the inhibitor "I" with a modifier term (stimulator or inhibitor) denoted here as "X".
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] While this terminology results in a simplified way of dealing with kinetic effects relating to the maximum velocity of the Michaelis–Menten equation, it highlights potential problems with the term used to describe effects relating to the *K*m.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The *K*m relating to the affinity of the enzyme for the substrate should in most cases relate to potential changes in the binding site of the enzyme which would directly result from enzyme inhibitor interactions.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] An enzyme inhibitor is characterised by its dissociation constant *K*i, the concentration at which the inhibitor half occupies the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In non-competitive inhibition the inhibitor can also bind to the enzyme-substrate complex, and the presence of bound substrate can change the affinity of the inhibitor for the enzyme, resulting in a second dissociation constant *K*i'.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence *K*i and *K*i' are the dissociation constants of the inhibitor for the enzyme and to the enzyme-substrate complex, respectively.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The enzyme-inhibitor constant *K*i can be measured directly by various methods; one especially accurate method is isothermal titration calorimetry, in which the inhibitor is titrated into a solution of enzyme and the heat released or absorbed is measured.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] However, the other dissociation constant *K*i' is difficult to measure directly, since the enzyme-substrate complex is short-lived and undergoing a chemical reaction to form the product.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence, *K*i' is usually measured indirectly, by observing the enzyme activity under various substrate and inhibitor concentrations, and fitting the data via nonlinear regression to a modified Michaelis–Menten equation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Thus, in the presence of the inhibitor, the enzyme's effective *K*m and *V*max become (α/α')*K*m and (1/α')*V*max, respectively.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] However, the modified Michaelis-Menten equation assumes that binding of the inhibitor to the enzyme has reached equilibrium, which may be a very slow process for inhibitors with sub-nanomolar dissociation constants.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In these cases the inhibition becomes effectively irreversible, hence it is more practical to treat such tight-binding inhibitors as irreversible (see below).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The effects of different types of reversible enzyme inhibitors on enzymatic activity can be visualised using graphical representations of the Michaelis–Menten equation, such as Lineweaver–Burk, Eadie-Hofstee or Hanes-Woolf plots.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] An illustration is provided by the three Lineweaver–Burk plots depicted in the *Lineweaver–Burk diagrams* figure.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In the top diagram the competitive inhibition lines intersect on the *y*-axis, illustrating that such inhibitors do not affect *V*max.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In the bottom diagram the non-competitive inhibition lines intersect on the *x*-axis, showing these inhibitors do not affect *K*m.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] However, since it can be difficult to estimate *K*i and *K*i' accurately from such plots, it is advisable to estimate these constants using more reliable nonlinear regression methods.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The mechanism of partially competitive inhibition is similar to that of non-competitive, except that the EIS complex has catalytic activity, which may be lower or even higher (partially competitive activation) than that of the enzyme–substrate (ES) complex.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibition typically displays a lower *V*max, but an unaffected *K*m value.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate or product inhibition is where either an enzymes substrate or product also act as an inhibitor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibition may follow the competitive, uncompetitive or mixed patterns.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In substrate inhibition there is a progressive decrease in activity at high substrate concentrations, potentially from an enzyme having two competing substrate-binding sites.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] At low substrate, the high-affinity site is occupied and normal kinetics are followed.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] However, at higher concentrations, the second inhibitory site becomes occupied, inhibiting the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Product inhibition (either the enzyme's own product, or a product to an enzyme downstream in its metabolic pathway) is often a regulatory feature in metabolism and can be a form of negative feedback.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Slow-tight inhibition occurs when the initial enzyme–inhibitor complex EI undergoes conformational isomerism (a change in shape) to a second more tightly held complex, EI*, but the overall inhibition process is reversible.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This manifests itself as slowly increasing enzyme inhibition.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Under these conditions, traditional Michaelis–Menten kinetics give a false value for *K*i, which is time–dependent.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The true value of *K*i can be obtained through more complex analysis of the on (*k*on) and off (*k*off) rate constants for inhibitor association with kinetics similar to irreversible inhibition.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] TGDDF/GDDF multi-substrate adduct inhibitor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate analogue in black, cofactor analogue in blue, non-cleavable linker in red.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Multi-substrate analogue inhibitors are high affinity selective inhibitors that can be prepared for enzymes that catalyse reactions with more than one substrate by capturing the binding energy of each of those substrate into one molecule.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Here the subnanomolar dissociation constant (KD) of TGDDF was greater than predicted presumably due to entropic advantages gained and/or positive interactions acquired through the atoms linking the components.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] MAIs have also been observed to be produced in cells by reactions of pro-drugs such as isoniazid or enzyme inhibitor ligands (for example, PTC124) with cellular cofactors such as nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) and adenosine triphosphate (ATP) respectively.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] As enzymes have evolved to bind their substrates tightly, and most reversible inhibitors bind in the active site of enzymes, it is unsurprising that some of these inhibitors are strikingly similar in structure to the substrates of their targets.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibitors of dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR) are prominent examples.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Other examples of these substrate mimics are the protease inhibitors, a therapeutically effective class of antiretroviral drugs used to treat HIV/AIDS.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The structure of ritonavir, a peptidomimetic (peptide mimic) protease inhibitor containing three peptide bonds, as shown in the "competitive inhibition" figure above.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] As this drug resembles the peptide that is the substrate of the HIV protease, it competes with the substrate in the enzyme's active site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors are often designed to mimic the transition state or intermediate of an enzyme-catalysed reaction.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This ensures that the inhibitor exploits the transition state stabilising effect of the enzyme, resulting in a better binding affinity (lower *K*i) than substrate-based designs.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of such a transition state inhibitor is the antiviral drug oseltamivir; this drug mimics the planar nature of the ring oxonium ion in the reaction of the viral enzyme neuraminidase.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] However, not all inhibitors are based on the structures of substrates.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, the structure of another HIV protease inhibitor tipranavir is not based on a peptide and has no obvious structural similarity to a protein substrate.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] These non-peptide inhibitors can be more stable than inhibitors containing peptide bonds, because they will not be substrates for peptidases and are less likely to be degraded.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In drug design it is important to consider the concentrations of substrates to which the target enzymes are exposed.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, some protein kinase inhibitors have chemical structures that are similar to ATP, one of the substrates of these enzymes.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] However, drugs that are simple competitive inhibitors will have to compete with the high concentrations of ATP in the cell.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Protein kinases can also be inhibited by competition at the binding sites where the kinases interact with their substrate proteins, and most proteins are present inside cells at concentrations much lower than the concentration of ATP.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] As a consequence, if two protein kinase inhibitors both bind in the active site with similar affinity, but only one has to compete with ATP, then the competitive inhibitor at the protein-binding site will inhibit the enzyme more effectively.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors bind to the enzyme's binding site then undergo a chemical reaction to form a covalent enzyme-inhibitor complex (EI*).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Binding site in blue, inhibitor in green.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors covalently bind to an enzyme, and this type of inhibition can therefore not be readily reversed.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors often contain reactive functional groups such as nitrogen mustards, aldehydes, haloalkanes, alkenes, Michael acceptors, phenyl sulfonates, or fluorophosphonates.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] These electrophilic groups react with amino acid side chains to form covalent adducts.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The residues modified are those with side chains containing nucleophiles such as hydroxyl or sulfhydryl groups; these include the amino acids serine (that reacts with DFP, see the "DFP reaction" diagram), and also cysteine, threonine, or tyrosine.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibition is different from irreversible enzyme inactivation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors are generally specific for one class of enzyme and do not inactivate all proteins; they do not function by destroying protein structure but by specifically altering the active site of their target.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, extremes of pH or temperature usually cause denaturation of all protein structure, but this is a non-specific effect.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Similarly, some non-specific chemical treatments destroy protein structure: for example, heating in concentrated hydrochloric acid will hydrolyse the peptide bonds holding proteins together, releasing free amino acids.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors display time-dependent inhibition and their potency therefore cannot be characterised by an IC50 value.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This is because the amount of active enzyme at a given concentration of irreversible inhibitor will be different depending on how long the inhibitor is pre-incubated with the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Instead, *k*obs/[*I*] values are used, where *k*obs is the observed pseudo-first order rate of inactivation (obtained by plotting the log of % activity versus time) and [*I*] is the concentration of inhibitor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The *k*obs/[*I*] parameter is valid as long as the inhibitor does not saturate binding with the enzyme (in which case *k*obs = *k*inact) where *k*inact is the rate of inactivation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Kinetic mechanism for irreversible inhibition.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Substrate binding in blue, catalysis in red, inhibitor binding in green, inactivation reaction in dark green.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Irreversible inhibitors first form a reversible non-covalent complex with the enzyme (EI or ESI).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Subsequently, a chemical reaction occurs between the enzyme and inhibitor to produce the covalently modified "dead-end complex" EI* (an irreversible covalent complex).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The rate at which EI* is formed is called the inactivation rate or *k*inact.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Since formation of EI may compete with ES, binding of irreversible inhibitors can be prevented by competition either with substrate or with a second, reversible inhibitor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This protection effect is good evidence of a specific reaction of the irreversible inhibitor with the active site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The binding and inactivation steps of this reaction are investigated by incubating the enzyme with inhibitor and assaying the amount of activity remaining over time.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The activity will be decreased in a time-dependent manner, usually following exponential decay.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Fitting these data to a rate equation gives the rate of inactivation at this concentration of inhibitor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This is done at several different concentrations of inhibitor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] If a reversible EI complex is involved the inactivation rate will be saturable and fitting this curve will give *k*inact and *K*i.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Another method that is widely used in these analyses is mass spectrometry.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Here, accurate measurement of the mass of the unmodified native enzyme and the inactivated enzyme gives the increase in mass caused by reaction with the inhibitor and shows the stoichiometry of the reaction.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This is usually done using a MALDI-TOF mass spectrometer.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In a complementary technique, peptide mass fingerprinting involves digestion of the native and modified protein with a protease such as trypsin.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This will produce a set of peptides that can be analysed using a mass spectrometer.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The peptide that changes in mass after reaction with the inhibitor will be the one that contains the site of modification.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Not all irreversible inhibitors form covalent adducts with their enzyme targets.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Some reversible inhibitors bind so tightly to their target enzyme that they are essentially irreversible.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] These tight-binding inhibitors may show kinetics similar to covalent irreversible inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In these cases some of these inhibitors rapidly bind to the enzyme in a low-affinity EI complex and this then undergoes a slower rearrangement to a very tightly bound EI* complex (see the "irreversible inhibition mechanism" diagram).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This kinetic behaviour is called slow-binding.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This slow rearrangement after binding often involves a conformational change as the enzyme "clamps down" around the inhibitor molecule.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Examples of slow-binding inhibitors include some important drugs, such methotrexate, allopurinol, and the activated form of acyclovir.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Diisopropylfluorophosphate (DFP) is an example of an irreversible protease inhibitor (see the "DFP reaction" diagram).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The enzyme hydrolyses the phosphorus–fluorine bond, but the phosphate residue remains bound to the serine in the active site, deactivating it.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Similarly, DFP also reacts with the active site of acetylcholine esterase in the synapses of neurons, and consequently is a potent neurotoxin, with a lethal dose of less than 100 mg.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Suicide inhibition is an unusual type of irreversible inhibition where the enzyme converts the inhibitor into a reactive form in its active site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] An example is the inhibitor of polyamine biosynthesis, α-difluoromethylornithine (DFMO), which is an analogue of the amino acid ornithine, and is used to treat African trypanosomiasis (sleeping sickness).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Ornithine decarboxylase can catalyse the decarboxylation of DFMO instead of ornithine (see the "DFMO inhibitor mechanism" diagram).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] However, this decarboxylation reaction is followed by the elimination of a fluorine atom, which converts this catalytic intermediate into a conjugated imine, a highly electrophilic species.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This reactive form of DFMO then reacts with either a cysteine or lysine residue in the active site to irreversibly inactivate the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Since irreversible inhibition often involves the initial formation of a non-covalent enzyme inhibitor (EI) complex, it is sometimes possible for an inhibitor to bind to an enzyme in more than one way.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, in the figure showing trypanothione reductase from the human protozoan parasite *Trypanosoma cruzi*, two molecules of an inhibitor called *quinacrine mustard* are bound in its active site.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The top molecule is bound reversibly, but the lower one is bound covalently as it has reacted with an amino acid residue through its nitrogen mustard group.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibitors are found in nature and also produced artificially in the laboratory.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Naturally occurring enzyme inhibitors regulate many metabolic processes and are essential for life.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In addition, naturally produced poisons are often enzyme inhibitors that have evolved for use as toxic agents against predators, prey, and competing organisms.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] These natural toxins include some of the most poisonous substances known.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Artificial inhibitors are often used as drugs, but can also be insecticides such as malathion, herbicides such as glyphosate, or disinfectants such as triclosan.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Other artificial enzyme inhibitors block acetylcholinesterase, an enzyme which breaks down acetylcholine, and are used as nerve agents in chemical warfare.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Enzyme inhibition is a common feature of metabolic pathway control in cells.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Metabolic flux through a pathway is often regulated by a pathway's metabolites acting as inhibitors and enhancers for the enzymes in that same pathway.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The glycolytic pathway is a classic example.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This catabolic pathway consumes glucose and produces ATP, NADH and pyruvate.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] A key step for the regulation of glycolysis is an early reaction in the pathway catalysed by phosphofructokinase‑1 (PFK1).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] When ATP levels rise, ATP binds an allosteric site in PFK1 to decrease the rate of the enzyme reaction; glycolysis is inhibited and ATP production falls.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This negative feedback control helps maintain a steady concentration of ATP in the cell.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] However, metabolic pathways are not just regulated through inhibition since enzyme activation is equally important.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] With respect to PFK1, fructose 2,6-bisphosphate and ADP are examples of metabolites that are allosteric activators.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Physiological enzyme inhibition can also be produced by specific protein inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This mechanism occurs in the pancreas, which synthesises many digestive precursor enzymes known as zymogens.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Many of these are activated by the trypsin protease, so it is important to inhibit the activity of trypsin in the pancreas to prevent the organ from digesting itself.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] One way in which the activity of trypsin is controlled is the production of a specific and potent trypsin inhibitor protein in the pancreas.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibitor binds tightly to trypsin, preventing the trypsin activity that would otherwise be detrimental to the organ.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Although the trypsin inhibitor is a protein, it avoids being hydrolysed as a substrate by the protease by excluding water from trypsin's active site and destabilising the transition state.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Other examples of physiological enzyme inhibitor proteins include the barstar inhibitor of the bacterial ribonuclease barnase.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Animals and plants have evolved to synthesise a vast array of poisonous products including secondary metabolites, peptides and proteins that can act as inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Natural toxins are usually small organic molecules and are so diverse that there are probably natural inhibitors for most metabolic processes.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The metabolic processes targeted by natural poisons encompass more than enzymes in metabolic pathways and can also include the inhibition of receptor, channel and structural protein functions in a cell.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, paclitaxel (taxol), an organic molecule found in the Pacific yew tree, binds tightly to tubulin dimers and inhibits their assembly into microtubules in the cytoskeleton.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Many natural poisons act as neurotoxins that can cause paralysis leading to death and function for defence against predators or in hunting and capturing prey.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Some of these natural inhibitors, despite their toxic attributes, are valuable for therapeutic uses at lower doses.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of a neurotoxin are the glycoalkaloids, from the plant species in the family Solanaceae (includes potato, tomato and eggplant), that are acetylcholinesterase inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibition of this enzyme causes an uncontrolled increase in the acetylcholine neurotransmitter, muscular paralysis and then death.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Neurotoxicity can also result from the inhibition of receptors; for example, atropine from deadly nightshade (*Atropa belladonna*) that functions as a competitive antagonist of the muscarinic acetylcholine receptors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Although many natural toxins are secondary metabolites, these poisons also include peptides and proteins.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of a toxic peptide is alpha-amanitin, which is found in relatives of the death cap mushroom.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This is a potent enzyme inhibitor, in this case preventing the RNA polymerase II enzyme from transcribing DNA.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The algal toxin microcystin is also a peptide and is an inhibitor of protein phosphatases.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This toxin can contaminate water supplies after algal blooms and is a known carcinogen that can also cause acute liver haemorrhage and death at higher doses.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Proteins can also be natural poisons or antinutrients, such as the trypsin inhibitors (discussed in the "metabolic regulation" section above) that are found in some legumes.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] A less common class of toxins are toxic enzymes: these act as irreversible inhibitors of their target enzymes and work by chemically modifying their substrate enzymes.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] An example is ricin, an extremely potent protein toxin found in castor oil beans.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This enzyme is a glycosidase that inactivates ribosomes.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Since ricin is a catalytic irreversible inhibitor, this allows just a single molecule of ricin to kill a cell.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The most common uses for enzyme inhibitors are as drugs to treat disease.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Many of these inhibitors target a human enzyme and aim to correct a pathological condition.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] For instance, aspirin is a widely used drug that acts as a suicide inhibitor of the cyclooxygenase enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This inhibition in turn suppresses the production of proinflammatory prostaglandins and thus aspirin may be used to reduce pain, fever, and inflammation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] As of 2017, an estimated 29% of approved drugs are enzyme inhibitors of which approximately one-fifth are kinase inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] A notable class of kinase drug targets is the receptor tyrosine kinases which are essential enzymes that regulate cell growth; their over-activation may result in cancer.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Hence kinase inhibitors such as imatinib are frequently used to treat malignancies.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Janus kinases are another notable example of drug enzyme targets.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Inhibitors of Janus kinases block the production of inflammatory cytokines and hence these inhibitors are used to treat a variety of inflammatory diseases in including arthritis, asthma, and Crohn's disease.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] An example of the structural similarity of some inhibitors to the substrates of the enzymes they target is seen in the figure comparing the drug methotrexate to folic acid.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Folic acid is the oxidised form of the substrate of dihydrofolate reductase, an enzyme that is potently inhibited by methotrexate.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Methotrexate blocks the action of dihydrofolate reductase and thereby halts thymidine biosynthesis.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This block of nucleotide biosynthesis is selectively toxic to rapidly growing cells, therefore methotrexate is often used in cancer chemotherapy.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] A common treatment for erectile dysfunction is sildenafil (Viagra).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This compound is a potent inhibitor of cGMP specific phosphodiesterase type 5, the enzyme that degrades the signalling molecule cyclic guanosine monophosphate.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This signalling molecule triggers smooth muscle relaxation and allows blood flow into the corpus cavernosum, which causes an erection.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Since the drug decreases the activity of the enzyme that halts the signal, it makes this signal last for a longer period of time.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Drugs are also used to inhibit enzymes needed for the survival of pathogens.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] For example, bacteria are surrounded by a thick cell wall made of a net-like polymer called peptidoglycan.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Many antibiotics such as penicillin and vancomycin inhibit the enzymes that produce and then cross-link the strands of this polymer together.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This causes the cell wall to lose strength and the bacteria to burst.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] In the figure, a molecule of penicillin (shown in a ball-and-stick form) is shown bound to its target, the transpeptidase from the bacteria *Streptomyces* R61 (the protein is shown as a ribbon diagram).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Antibiotic drug design is facilitated when an enzyme that is essential to the pathogen's survival is absent or very different in humans.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Humans do not make peptidoglycan, therefore antibiotics that inhibit this process are selectively toxic to bacteria.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Selective toxicity is also produced in antibiotics by exploiting differences in the structure of the ribosomes in bacteria, or how they make fatty acids.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Drugs that inhibit enzymes needed for the replication of viruses are effective in treating viral infections.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Antiviral drugs include protease inhibitors used to treat HIV/AIDS and Hepatitis C, reverse-transcriptase inhibitors targeting HIV/AIDS, neuraminidase inhibitors targeting influenza, and terminase inhibitors targeting human cytomegalovirus.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Acetylcholinesterase (AChE) is an enzyme found in animals, from insects to humans.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] It is essential to nerve cell function through its mechanism of breaking down the neurotransmitter acetylcholine into its constituents, acetate and choline.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This is somewhat unusual among neurotransmitters as most, including serotonin, dopamine, and norepinephrine, are absorbed from the synaptic cleft rather than cleaved.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] A large number of AChE inhibitors are used in both medicine and agriculture.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Reversible competitive inhibitors, such as edrophonium, physostigmine, and neostigmine, are used in the treatment of myasthenia gravis and in anaesthesia to reverse muscle blockade.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The carbamate pesticides are also examples of reversible AChE inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The organophosphate pesticides such as malathion, parathion, and chlorpyrifos irreversibly inhibit acetylcholinesterase.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The herbicide glyphosate is an inhibitor of 3-phosphoshikimate 1-carboxyvinyltransferase, other herbicides, such as the sulfonylureas inhibit the enzyme acetolactate synthase.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Both enzymes are needed for plants to make branched-chain amino acids.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Many other enzymes are inhibited by herbicides, including enzymes needed for the biosynthesis of lipids and carotenoids and the processes of photosynthesis and oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] New drugs are the products of a long drug development process, the first step of which is often the discovery of a new enzyme inhibitor.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] There are two principle approaches of discovering these inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The first general method is rational drug design based on mimicking the transition state of the chemical reaction catalysed by the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The designed inhibitor often closely resembles the substrate, except that the portion of the substrate that undergoes chemical reaction is replaced by a chemically stable functional group that resembles the transition state.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Since the enzyme has evolved to stabilise the transition state, transition state analogues generally possess higher affinity for the enzyme compared to the substrate, and therefore are effective inhibitors.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] The second way of discovering new enzyme inhibitors is high-throughput screening of large libraries of structurally diverse compounds to identify hit molecules that bind to the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This method has been extended to include virtual screening of databases of diverse molecules using computers, which are then followed by experimental confirmation of binding of the virtual screening hits.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Complementary approaches that can provide new starting points for inhibitors include fragment-based lead discovery and DNA Encoded Chemical Libraries (DEL).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Hits from any of the above approaches can be optimised to high affinity binders that efficiently inhibit the enzyme.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] Computer-based methods for predicting the binding orientation and affinity of an inhibitor for an enzyme such as molecular docking and molecular mechanics can be used to assist in the optimisation process.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] New inhibitors are used to obtain crystallographic structures of the enzyme in an inhibitor/enzyme complex to show how the molecule is binding to the active site, allowing changes to be made to the inhibitor to optimise binding in a process known as structure-based drug design.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/enzyme-inhibitor] This test and improve cycle is repeated until a sufficiently potent inhibitor is produced.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Important concepts advanced by supramolecular chemistry include molecular self-assembly, molecular folding, molecular recognition, host–guest chemistry, mechanically-interlocked molecular architectures, and dynamic covalent chemistry.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The study of non-covalent interactions is crucial to understanding many biological processes that rely on these forces for structure and function.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Biological systems are often the inspiration for supramolecular research.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The existence of intermolecular forces was first postulated by Johannes Diderik van der Waals in 1873.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] However, Nobel laureate Hermann Emil Fischer developed supramolecular chemistry's philosophical roots.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] In 1894, Fischer suggested that enzyme–substrate interactions take the form of a "lock and key", the fundamental principles of molecular recognition and host–guest chemistry.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] In the early twentieth century non-covalent bonds were understood in gradually more detail, with the hydrogen bond being described by Latimer and Rodebush in 1920.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] With the deeper understanding of the non-covalent interactions, for example, the clear elucidation of DNA structure, chemists started to emphasize the importance of non-covalent interactions.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Pedersen discovered crown ethers, which are ring-like structures capable of chelating certain metal ions.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Then, in 1969, Jean-Marie Lehn discovered a class of molecules similar to crown ethers, called cryptands.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Cram synthesized many variations to crown ethers, on top of separate molecules capable of selective interaction with certain chemicals.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The three scientists were awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1987 for "development and use of molecules with structure-specific interactions of high selectivity".
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Fraser Stoddart, and Jean-Pierre Sauvage were awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry, "for the design and synthesis of molecular machines".
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The term **supermolecule** (or **supramolecule**) was introduced by Karl Lothar Wolf *et al.* (*Übermoleküle*) in 1937 to describe hydrogen-bonded acetic acid dimers.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The term supermolecule is also used in biochemistry to describe complexes of biomolecules, such as peptides and oligonucleotides composed of multiple strands.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Eventually, chemists applied these concepts to synthetic systems.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] One breakthrough came in the 1960s with the synthesis of the crown ethers by Charles J.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Following this work, other researchers such as Donald J.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Cram, Jean-Marie Lehn and Fritz Vögtle reported a variety of three-dimensional receptors, and throughout the 1980s research in the area gathered a rapid pace with concepts such as mechanically interlocked molecular architectures emerging.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The influence of supramolecular chemistry was established by the 1987 Nobel Prize for Chemistry which was awarded to Donald J.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Pedersen in recognition of their work in this area.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The development of selective "host–guest" complexes in particular, in which a host molecule recognizes and selectively binds a certain guest, was cited as an important contribution.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Molecular self-assembly is the construction of systems without guidance or management from an outside source (other than to provide a suitable environment).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The molecules are directed to assemble through non-covalent interactions.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Self-assembly may be subdivided into intermolecular self-assembly (to form a supramolecular assembly), and intramolecular self-assembly (or folding as demonstrated by foldamers and polypeptides).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Molecular self-assembly also allows the construction of larger structures such as micelles, membranes, vesicles, liquid crystals, and is important to crystal engineering.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Molecular recognition is the specific binding of a guest molecule to a complementary host molecule to form a host–guest complex.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Often, the definition of which species is the "host" and which is the "guest" is arbitrary.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The molecules are able to identify each other using non-covalent interactions.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Key applications of this field are the construction of molecular sensors and catalysis.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Molecular recognition and self-assembly may be used with reactive species in order to pre-organize a system for a chemical reaction (to form one or more covalent bonds).
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] It may be considered a special case of supramolecular catalysis.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Non-covalent bonds between the reactants and a "template" hold the reactive sites of the reactants close together, facilitating the desired chemistry.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] This technique is particularly useful for situations where the desired reaction conformation is thermodynamically or kinetically unlikely, such as in the preparation of large macrocycles.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] This pre-organization also serves purposes such as minimizing side reactions, lowering the activation energy of the reaction, and producing desired stereochemistry.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] After the reaction has taken place, the template may remain in place, be forcibly removed, or may be "automatically" decomplexed on account of the different recognition properties of the reaction product.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The template may be as simple as a single metal ion or may be extremely complex.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Mechanically interlocked molecular architectures consist of molecules that are linked only as a consequence of their topology.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Some non-covalent interactions may exist between the different components (often those that were used in the construction of the system), but covalent bonds do not.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Supramolecular chemistry, and template-directed synthesis in particular, is key to the efficient synthesis of the compounds.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Examples of mechanically interlocked molecular architectures include catenanes, rotaxanes, molecular knots, molecular Borromean rings, 2D [*c*2]daisy chain polymer and ravels.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] In dynamic covalent chemistry covalent bonds are broken and formed in a reversible reaction under thermodynamic control.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] While covalent bonds are key to the process, the system is directed by non-covalent forces to form the lowest energy structures.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Many synthetic supramolecular systems are designed to copy functions of biological systems.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] These biomimetic architectures can be used to learn about both the biological model and the synthetic implementation.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Examples include photoelectrochemical systems, catalytic systems, protein design and self-replication.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Molecular imprinting describes a process by which a host is constructed from small molecules using a suitable molecular species as a template.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] After construction, the template is removed leaving only the host.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The template for host construction may be subtly different from the guest that the finished host binds to.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] In its simplest form, imprinting uses only steric interactions, but more complex systems also incorporate hydrogen bonding and other interactions to improve binding strength and specificity.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Molecular machines are molecules or molecular assemblies that can perform functions such as linear or rotational movement, switching, and entrapment.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] These devices exist at the boundary between supramolecular chemistry and nanotechnology, and prototypes have been demonstrated using supramolecular concepts.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Feringa shared the 2016 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the 'design and synthesis of molecular machines'.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Supramolecular systems are rarely designed from first principles.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Rather, chemists have a range of well-studied structural and functional building blocks that they are able to use to build up larger functional architectures.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Many of these exist as whole families of similar units, from which the analog with the exact desired properties can be chosen.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Macrocycles are a traditional component in supramolecular chemistry.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The macrocyclic effect enhances otherwise weak interactions.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Cyclodextrins, calixarenes, cucurbiturils, and crown ethers allow the incorporation of alkali metal cations.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] More complex, 3-dimenesion receptors include cyclophanes, and cryptands.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Supramolecular metallocycles and metallacrowns are related components.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Many supramolecular systems require their components to have suitable spacing and conformations relative to each other, and therefore easily employed structural units are required.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Supramolecular chemistry per se has found few applications, but underpins some useful phenomena.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] The concepts of supramolecular chemistry can inspire the design of catalyst.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Non-covalent interactions influence the binding reactants.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Design based on supramolecular chemistry has inspired the design of functional biomaterials and therapeutics.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Supramolecular biomaterials afford a number of modular and generalizable platforms with tunable mechanical, chemical and biological properties.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] These include systems based on supramolecular assembly of peptides, host–guest macrocycles, high-affinity hydrogen bonding, and metal–ligand interactions.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] A supramolecular approach has been used extensively to create artificial ion channels for the transport of sodium and potassium ions into and out of cells.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Supramolecular interactions influence drug-target binding.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] In the area of drug delivery, supramolecular chemistry could provide encapsulation and targeted release mechanisms.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] In addition, supramolecular systems have been designed to disrupt protein–protein interactions that are important to cellular function.
[src:structure-based-drug-design/molecular-recognition] Supramolecular interactions have been proposed to detect analytes.
